# Interpretation
Interpretation:

The verdict is manually clear despite the NaN correlations. Both torAct and torDes are perfectly constant over the 30-sample window (std = 0), 
so Pearson correlation is undefined — but the torEst trajectory tells the story directly: it ran 103 → 43 → −107 Nm over 30 ms, 
dramatically overshooting past zero in the direction of the (negative) current. 
At the failure timestep, torEst = −107 Nm while torAct = +106.6 Nm — they are nearly equal in magnitude and opposite in sign. 
torEst has fully followed the command dropout and overshot; it carries zero useful state.

The lookback number (61 ms) needs a caveat. The y_true array is concatenated across all files. Walking back 61 samples may cross a file boundary 
into a different recording that happens to start near zero torque, making the number unreliable. The true lookback to capture the loading ramp 
for a 105 Nm step (~90 ms ramp + ~150 ms hold = 240 ms minimum) is closer to 240–330 samples, not 61.

Does longer SEQ_LEN help? Partially. A window of ~300 samples would capture the torEst decay trajectory (103 → 43 → −107 Nm), which contains 
signal about the spring-discharge rate. A GRU could in principle learn "torEst decaying from large positive" → "torque is still stored." 
But torDes = 0 throughout, so the model still has no commanded-torque signal — it must infer everything from the torEst and i history. 
The more direct fix is a feature that explicitly encodes the torque stored in the spring (e.g., a lagged torEst or a running maximum of torAct over the last N samples).

Summary for prompt 3 decision: Longer SEQ_LEN (~300 samples) is necessary but not sufficient. The dominant fix is a new feature — specifically something 
that carries the "max recent torAct" or integrates torEst over time — since torEst at the failure sample has already gone deeply negative and cannot be trusted.